properties.mosquitohabitatmapperComments: I haven’t seen any mosquitos moving around here, and it’s a man-made ditch my parents made to curb the growth of bamboo. Unfortunately, it fills up with water every time it rains. Although no mosquitos were present when observing, the shade and still water make it an ideal place for breeding. My parents complain of mosquito bites every time to work in the garden close to the bamboo, so I suspect there should be some mosquito larvae somewhere. I’ve taken a sample of the water and will wait to see if there are any larvae developments. There were some small insects on the surface of the water, although they looked more like small flies than mosquitos.

properties.mosquitohabitatmapperComments: This area of my backyard has always been barren, and we’ve tried to fill all the patches with grass, it it’s still very marshy. It’s almost like a mini swamp. Whenever it rains or snows, this particular strip is always mushy and wet, making it another potential mosquito breeding ground, as the conditions match, but I haven’t seen any larvae in the water yet.

properties.mosquitohabitatmapperComments: This is a mosquito larvae trap that I built and filled with lemon juice mixed with water. It has been sitting on my back porch for over a week since I last checked it, and it has not yielded any mosquito larvae. The only major thing I observed in this trap was the red gelatinous substance floating in the top, caught on the netting meant to keep mosquitoes in the trap from getting out. When I moved the trap, the substance didn't dissipate- it stayed in one piece still caught on the netting. There was a little more of it at the bottom of my trap, but it was separated into pieces and lighter in color.

properties.mosquitohabitatmapperComments: This is a mosquito larvae trap that I built and filled with sugar water. After leaving it in a tree for 6 days, I checked it. There were no mosquito larvae in the trap, just some large dead ants. The sugar water had fermented a bit, so I poured it out and refilled it with new suagr water. I put the trap back in the tree, and will be checking it again sometime next week.
properties.organizationName: United States of America Citizen Science

properties.mosquitohabitatmapperComments: This is a mosquito larvae trap that I built and filled with salt water. After leaving it in the woods off of a nature trail for 6 days, I checked it. It had been knocked over, but there was still some salt water in it. However, there were no mosquito larvae in the trap. I refilled the salt water, put the trap back (making sure it was extra secure), and will be checking it again some time next week.
properties.organizationName: United States of America Citizen Science
